Since listening to that Lord of Spirits episode (I believe "Eating With The Gods") where they explain how in the Bible the basis of family is just eating together and worship is most strictly defined as sharing a meal with a god I can never see extended family meetings the same.

Getting together at a table and even sharing just black coffee and digestive biscuits immediately reinforces group coherence and the family structure. And actually sharing a meal with a stranger is an enormous responsibility on the other side. "Lunch table memes" are too telling.

If you look up that Steven Seagal reggae album where he sings the infamous "mi wan the poonani" line ("Songs from the Crystal Cove") the reviewers say it's shit but can't give it less than 2.5 stars because it's "endearing in its own way" and has "good vibes". Lesson in here.

As long as the vibes are good you can get away with a lot without too big of a problem. Might not be too talented or a genius at all, but if you keep the vibes up it's mostly ok in the end. No one will get too mad at you for trying to make something fun that can cheer others up.
